\f0\b\fs48 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Custom Memory Allocator\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 A from-scratch implementation of 
\f2\fs26 malloc
\f1\fs24 , 
\f2\fs26 free
\f1\fs24 , 
\f2\fs26 realloc
\f1\fs24 , and 
\f2\fs26 calloc
\f1\fs24  in C. No standard library allocator functions are used. Everything runs on top of raw 
\f2\fs26 sbrk
\f1\fs24  and 
\f2\fs26 mmap
\f1\fs24  system calls.\
Built as part of a summer portfolio project to understand what actually happens when you call 
\f2\fs26 malloc
\f1\fs24 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 What this is\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 When you write 
\f2\fs26 malloc(32)
\f1\fs24  in C, the standard library does a lot of work behind the scenes: it finds a free chunk of heap memory, tracks it, and hands you a pointer. This project implements all of that from scratch.\
The allocator supports three different strategies for finding free memory, and they all get benchmarked against each other to show the trade-offs between speed and fragmentation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

