\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 How it works\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 The block header\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Every chunk of managed memory has a small header placed right before it:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 typedef struct Block \{\
    size_t   size;      // usable bytes after this header\
    int      is_free;   // 1 = available, 0 = in use\
    uint32_t magic;     // corruption and double-free detection\
    struct Block *next;\
    struct Block *prev;\
\} Block;\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 On 64-bit systems this is 32 bytes. The layout in memory looks like:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 [ header ][ user data ][ header ][ user data ]...\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Given a user pointer, recovering the header is always 
\f2\fs26 (Block*)ptr - 1
\f1\fs24 . This one pattern is used everywhere.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 The three strategies\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 First-fit
\f1\b0  scans the block list and returns the first free block that is big enough. Fast, but tends to fragment the beginning of the heap with small leftovers over time.\

\f0\b Best-fit
\f1\b0  scans the entire list and returns the smallest block that fits. Produces less fragmentation than first-fit but is slower because it always does a full scan.\

\f0\b Buddy system
\f1\b0  is a completely different approach. Every block is a power-of-two size. When memory is needed, a large block is repeatedly halved until the smallest power-of-two that fits is reached. When freed, a block merges with its "buddy" (the other half of the split) if the buddy is also free. Finding the buddy uses XOR arithmetic and is O(1). Allocation is O(log n). The trade-off is internal fragmentation: a 33-byte request gets a 64-byte block, wasting 31 bytes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Switching strategies\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs26 \cf0 set_strategy(STRATEGY_FIRST_FIT);   // default\
set_strategy(STRATEGY_BEST_FIT);\
set_strategy(STRATEGY_BUDDY);\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Safety features\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 Two magic number constants are used to detect memory bugs:\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs26 \cf0 #define MAGIC_ALLOC 0xDEADBEEF   // block is in use\
#define MAGIC_FREE  0xDEADDEAD   // block was freed\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf0 Every block gets 
\f2\fs26 MAGIC_ALLOC
\f1\fs24  stamped on it when allocated. On free, the magic field is checked first. If it is already 
\f2\fs26 MAGIC_FREE
\f1\fs24 , the call is a double-free and is rejected with an error message. If it is anything other than 
\f2\fs26 MAGIC_ALLOC
\f1\fs24 , the pointer is invalid and is also rejected. Neither case crashes the program.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
