\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 What I learned\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 A few things that were not obvious going in:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Coalescing cannot call malloc or free internally.
\f1\b0  The first version of coalesce called my_free to mark a block as free before merging it. That causes infinite recursion because my_free calls coalesce, which calls my_free, and so on. Coalescing has to do pointer surgery directly on the existing blocks.\

\f0\b The magic field has to be reset on reuse.
\f1\b0  When my_malloc reuses a freed block, it has to stamp MAGIC_ALLOC back on it. Missing this meant the next free call would see MAGIC_FREE and incorrectly report a double-free, which is exactly what showed up in the thread safety test before the fix.\

\f0\b Unlocking before calling another locked function.
\f1\b0  my_realloc sometimes needs to call my_malloc and my_free internally for its fallback path. Since all three functions lock the same mutex, my_realloc has to unlock before making those calls. Forgetting this causes a deadlock that only shows up under concurrent load.\

\f0\b Best-fit does not always produce less fragmentation.
\f1\b0  The theory says best-fit should fragment less than first-fit. In practice, because best-fit always picks the tightest match, it tends to leave many tiny unusable remainders. On random-size workloads the difference is real (0.19 vs 0.34) but best-fit is not the clear winner the theory suggests.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Known limitations\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Single global mutex
\f1\b0 : all allocations are serialised. Under high thread contention this is the main bottleneck. Per-thread arenas (how jemalloc and tcmalloc work) would fix this.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 No mmap fallback for large allocations
\f1\b0 : everything goes through sbrk. Real allocators use mmap for requests above ~128KB so those chunks can be returned to the OS on free.\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 O(n) allocation for first-fit and best-fit
\f1\b0 : both scan the full free list. Segregated free lists (one list per size class) would make typical allocations O(1).\
\ls3\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Fixed-size buddy pool
\f1\b0 : the buddy system is backed by a static 64KB array. A real implementation would grow on demand.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
